segments.text: Nolan Estes was the superintendent of schools in Dallas.
It was the one that was here in 1970 in February that made the presentation, our graduate student and faculty.
And this was, again, one of these things that Frank Hubert had done.
He put together a series of seminars for the graduate students in which all the graduate students from throughout the college would participate, in which they would participate.
Which, again, wanting to have them
be exposed to named people in the field, as well as having them be able to meet those individuals.
But it's interesting how the graduate students reacted to that.
It was required.
So they liked it very well.
I find it very interesting today we have graduate students in our department that are asking for such.
If we required it, that's what they would like it.
That's funny.
Do you feel, then, that this
has helped in how this college is viewed by outsiders?
Because this is so unique, and it's something that just evolved, and it has only happened here.
Is that?
I don't know as very many people, even within the college, even know about how that has really evolved and how it functions today, because it does function so much like a department.
Just a little aside about how these things can benefit and create attitudes and so forth.
I referenced earlier that I was always able to get the good faculty to teach, but there was a line item that I referenced earlier in the Ed Psych budget for a vocational guidance type person.
After Dr.
Bowman went into other responsibilities and a couple people went through that line, one year that line was not filled by Ed Psych.
And here I was with a array of courses to teach, and I didn't have a faculty member to teach that course because I had to go to Ed Psych to get it.
I had to hire someone on a temporary basis to just teach that course.
We were doing many of the courses off campus, and our philosophy was to use our on-campus faculty, full-time faculty, to teach those.
So in putting my budget together that year, I moved the line from Ed Psych to
I went in to see, to share my budget with Thank You Britain, not anticipating that that line would be moved at all.

I was simply using that as a political ploy to make a point with him that, hey, I was sure the faculty member at psych was looking for a different, more of an educational psychology type person than a cadence type person.
He turned around and picked up the phone and called Art Roach, who was in the department, and asked Art if they'd filled that position yet.
Art said, no.
He said, well, that line item will be in the IDE next year.
Well, he made that decision based upon a need that was out there, but you can imagine the attitude toward Don Clark for a little while right then.
And so how do attitudes get evolved?
Maybe that was a cold decision he made.
From my perspective, it was one that needed to be made, and he made it in a straightforward manner, and no guessing on the part of insight why he made it.
It was simply something, do you want to fill the position?
We'll move it someplace else.
That's right.
And I guess in a sense, that was another start for putting faculty lines in IDED.
And from then on, we started doing that.
And we, quite truthfully, we gained some things with it, but we also lost some of that ability to draw faculty from wherever, even though we still do that.
As you know, I teach IDED courses.
Dr. Christensen at Agriculture Education teaches them.
We draw from various departments, but not to the degree that we used to.
Do you think that there's more collaboration in that area, in this area, than there is among other departments in the college?
Because I've noticed that there's not a whole lot, as much as people would like, you know, collaboration because of the fact that it's grown so much and everybody's doing their thing.
There's a lot of specialty areas now, and people are being hired just for one particular.
I think the interdisciplinary education program has potential that was never realized because we ended up
making it a department rather than keeping it interdisciplinary as a holding tank for developing new programs.

If we had kept it truly interdisciplinary as a holding tank mechanism, as a collaborative arrangement, it would have served a better function maybe than what it has where we have, in essence, made it a department.
Okay, as all of this has evolved, one of the things that has happened and has been happening not only in the college but at Texas A&M is the tremendous growth.
Has that affected the way you work with students?
I know I'm hearing things like,
A&M is getting, you know, the standards are so high now that we're not getting the students in that made A&M.
They can't get in anymore.
How do you perceive, you know, what has happened with students?
Well, we might divide that into two aspects, both at the undergraduate level and at the graduate level.
Okay.
Let me speak first to the graduate level.
That's when I've been most involved with the last couple of years, but the graduate level,
And we, especially in my role here in the Department of Education, we pride ourselves with the open door policy with a lot of good student interactions.

This morning I had a student from New York that was here on campus and he felt comfortable coming in and sitting here for an hour talking about not only his academic program, but also professional goals and some personal problems and so forth.
I think the
academic rigor of the department, the college, the university can only enhance the graduate program.
And I don't see us being any less, in this department at least, I think I have to underscore the word this department, any less open to spending time with the students in counseling and so forth.
At the undergraduate level, I'm afraid there's a couple of things that are happening that maybe will have some impact, and that's part of what you're talking about, Sylvia, or Kim.
Can the students who used to major in industrial education now get into the program?
In industrial education, we are unique in that we have many, many more seniors than we have freshmen.
In fact, we have many more second semester juniors than we have first semester juniors.
It's at the end of the sophomore year, the junior year, when people transfer from other majors to industrial education.
They have finally convinced dad and mother and themselves that engineering is probably not the best place for them.
Looking for other, maybe in terms of academics, but
the high theory that is needed in engineering programs today.

I feel that industrial education, whether it be the teacher certification program or whether it be the industrial employment program, is an excellent place for 20 students to come into if we could just get them before they got in all the green point problems.
And I'm afraid, I'm afraid that the academic standards are maybe going to be cutting out some people that would be available for us in that major.
The counseling of students, again, we pride ourselves in counseling with undergraduate students.
We are a small department, so I think we are able to do more individual counseling.
Every faculty member takes that as a personal responsibility.

I think as you look at our doors, you'll find the mentor, the Aggie mentor name on most of our doors, more so than any, percentage-wise, I'm sorry, I'm certain it's more than most any other department.
some other departments in our college.
I know that most of the undergraduate advisement is done by one or two people.
And we, even though they're much larger departments, ours is a smaller department, we're all involved in that.
We pride ourselves in that.
Because that's part of your teaching.
Absolutely.
I mean, it's so important to teaching.
It's a part of it.
I guess that's just a part of the philosophy of our industrial education.
And maybe it's Ron and I, I think we
pride ourselves in our student contact.
Does each department have a philosophy as such?

Whether it's written down or not, probably not, but even if there's a mission goal, even if there's a mission goal and philosophical statement written, I think more importantly there is a philosophy that emerges.
Can you capsulize that in your department?
Because I've only had one more department.
I didn't have that as a question.
I know that
the mission or the goal of the College of Education, but I haven't.

I guess right now, except for being student-oriented, there are at least four things that are happening now in our department that are somewhat a little hard to say exactly the philosophy, the mission statement, and so forth.
And one of those, of course, would be the change right now from department head to interim department head to where we're going in the future.
And that's where we're going in the future is one of the things that is very time consuming on faculty, very frustrating on students, and .
Is there any clue of where it might be headed at this point?
I think, as a faculty, I would hope that we would stay intact as an administrative unit.
We are a nationally recognized program cluster.
and the dean has assured us that we are not going to be dissolved but we've not seen that evidence and I think that's a difference in the style of leadership of the two deans.
We need to evolve where we're going before we have a new department that's going to help us get there and I find that a little bit awkward.
So with that change there's some awkwardness in it.
With the change in the whole
a five-year program that we're changing the total teacher education program within not only the university but within the state.
That is another factor that is playing on the corridor.
And then, of course, the legislation thing.
So we have at least, I said four, but at least the three would be state mandates, university changes, departmental changes.
Those three are ones that are, but through it all, I think we can still say we are very much a student
Well, you answered a little bit about the future.
There's one that, if you haven't picked up on your tape someplace, and you might get this from some of the adult ed people, about the off-campus mission of the college.
One of the things that we've done in adult and extension and vocational education, more so than other departments, is taken our program, especially at the graduate level, to the people.
And you're familiar with this, of course, in San Antonio.
EDCI is now doing this somewhat, they're taking some courses to Key and to Temple.
But using the off-campus
instructional mode as a way of meeting a need.
I guess this is, again, maybe we can talk about philosophy.
Our philosophy is that we do take part of our program to the constituent.
Again, trying to meet their individual needs, I think, is an important philosophy rather than that everybody must come here to be .
Well, it's been extremely helpful, and it's growing by leaps and bounds.
And it's a wonderful service, because I don't know how a lot of these people can possibly do it.
And at least, even if they have to come here ultimately, just the fact that they have that linkage and they start with that, then it's motivating to end up here eventually, which is good.
I might hit a little bit of you already have on some of the highlights and your contributions specifically, and some insights and observations.
What about the future as the 21st century emerges?
Just for the College of Education, do you have any kind of a perception of where it might be?
One of the things that I've used is people have bemoaned the five-year program.
If we reflect back in earlier years, say my mother graduated high school in May and started teaching in September with a certificate by going to a two-week workshop.

In 1932, it was when the University of Wisconsin-Stout and Stout State Institute and Oswego in New York were two colleges in industrial education that went from the two-year normal school program to the four-year baccalaureate program.
I wonder what the debate was in the mid-thirties about moving from a two-year normal school to a four-year degree.
I imagine the debate was equally as lively as it is today, moving from a four-year program to a five- or a six-year program.

I would judge that 20 years from now, we will see the master's program, it won't be that long, 10 years from now, we'll see the master's program as much an integral part of the teacher education program as we do the baccalaureate today, and I draw the analogy to the two-year normal school syndrome of years past.

I think what I keep hearing from people that are out there is, you know, because teachers are not paid, you know, in comparison to some of the other professions, how do you justify making them have to stay five years in college as expensive as college costs or as much as college costs are rising when they're going to come out making $18,000?
You know, that's where I think there's a lot of this, you know, fear that people are just
It's very hard to recruit for the College of Education right now because the counselors are saying, you know, kids don't want to go into education.
And that's a, you know, we've got to overcome that.
It's one of these kids don't want to.
It's one of these self-fulfilling prophecies.
We're right now looking at a mentorship minority recruitment proposal.
And we're looking at a minority recruitment proposal.
in which we're wanting to write in mentors in there.
I just wrote down Fidel Castillo as an industrial education mentor.
And looking at individuals out there of any ethnic background that would recruit people into the profession.
And I think the teachers are needed to have a more positive attitude.
I might reflect back on the Interdisciplinary Education Program.

There were, for a number of years, the students who were associated with the Interdisciplinary Education Program, adult education students, vocational education students, thought they had the best of both worlds.
They were really, really very positive about the program they were in.
And then we got a couple of faculty members in who were associated with IDED who
wondered who they were, where they were, what department.
They were searching for identity of the department.
And Sylvia, that immediately, the graduate students in that department had questions.
Who are we?
Where are we?
Where do we belong?
And two years before that, they were very positive.
But the influence of two faculty members who asked that question influenced the whole group.
I agree.

There's one that's not on tape, but it needs to be on there, and that's one of the most rewarding experiences I've had, and that was working with the College of Education Development Council and being the Associate Dean for Research during the initial evolutionary days of that.
And I think this is a program that will be a function
a committee, a council that will assist us in two ways as we continue to evolve to the future.
One is in funding, which of course is one reason for the Development Council.

But the other is we're using our Development Council in the College of Education is also for, because we don't have advisory committees, industrial advisory committees and so forth, we're also using the Development Council as a programmatic advisor sometimes.

But I think that the assistance that we get from the quality of people we have on advisory council can't help but be a positive influence on both the programmatic thrust as well as the where we're all to get to.
And it's very important to keep that momentum that started when you had it.
And I feel it's like being part of the beginning and being a part of it now.
I feel like we need something to get everybody together and keep that momentum, because that's so important.
Otherwise, people start to play.
And we have some fantastic people in there that can just really benefit a lot.

When this study is done, and maybe 20 years from now, when somebody has to take an ed-ad course and pick up a dissertation and study or evaluate, and they read about the history of the College of Education, is there something that you would like in there that would be just
a statement of your contribution or what you would like to be remembered down the line as something that was meaningful.
I've highlighted two things.
One was the opportunity to be at the right place at the right time during the expansion time of the college where we could use fairly good appropriated dollars.
soft money dollars, contracting grant dollars to help evolve additional programs in the college and then to be able to see them evolve into full fully funded programs.
One that I mentioned before was Bob Riley's college student program.
He had a funded project for that that also assisted in evolving that program to where it is today.
And then the other ones I just now mentioned was the
Development Council, I'd like to, I wonder what the history, you and I both wonder what the history of that council will be 20 years from now.
That's right, but it was exciting to have been on the ground floor, and I know I feel very fortunate to have been chosen, and I still don't know how that ever happened.
I thank you, Dr. Barker.
This has been very informative and very interesting, and I look forward to visiting some more.
